05797nam a22007095i 9780822383819DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20032003ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223838197 a10.1515/97808223838192doi  a(DE-B1597)552602  a(OCoLC)1055302108  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aGF668bC87 2003 7aBUS0720002bisacsh04a333.7/2/095900aCulture and the Question of Rights :bForests, Coasts, and Seas in Southeast Asia /ced. by Charles Zerner. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b16 b&w photos, 7 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Moving Translations: Poetics, Performance, and Propertyin Indonesia and Malaysia -- tCultivating theWild: Honey-Hunting and Forest Management in Southeast Kalimantan -- tSounding the Makassar Strait: The Poetics and Politics of an Indonesian Marine Environment -- tSingers of the Landscape: Song, History,and PropertyR ights in the Malaysian Rainforest -- tWriting for Their Lives: Bentian Dayak Authors and Indonesian Development Discourse -- tFruit Trees and FamilyTrees in an Anthropogenic Forest: PropertyZones, Resource Access, and Environmental Change in Indonesia -- tReflections: Toward New Conceptions of Rights -- tAfterword. By Land and By Sea: Reflections on Claims and Communities in the Malay Archipelago -- tWorks Cited -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis collection of ethnographic and interpretive essays fundamentally alters the debate over indigenous land claims in Southeast Asia and beyond. Based on fieldwork conducted in Malaysia and Indonesia during the 1980s and 1990s, these studies explore new terrain at the intersection of environmental justice, nature conservation, cultural performance, and the politics of making and interpreting claims.Calling for radical redefinitions of development and ownership and for new understandings of the translation of culture and rights in politically dangerous contexts—natural resource frontiers—this volume links social injustice and the degradation of Southeast Asian environments. Charles Zerner and his colleagues show how geographical areas once viewed as wild and undeveloped are actually cultural artifacts shaped by complex interactions with human societies. Drawing on richly varied sources of evidence and interpretation—from trance dances, court proceedings, tree planting patterns, marine and forest rituals, erotic poems, and codifications of customary law, Culture and the Question of Rights reveals the ironies, complexities, and histories of contemporary communities’ struggles to retain their gardens, forests, fishing territories, and graveyards. The contributors examine how these cultural activities work to both construct and to lay claim to nature. These essays open up new avenues for negotiating indigenous rights against a background of violence, proliferating markets, and global ideas of biodiversity and threatened habitat.Contributors. Jane Atkinson, Don Brenneis, Stephanie Fried, Nancy Peluso, Marina Roseman, Anna Tsing, Charles Zerner  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCivil rightszSoutheast Asia. 0aConservation of natural resourceszSoutheast Asia. 0aEthnologyzSoutheast Asia. 0aHuman ecologyzSoutheast Asia. 0aLand tenurexGovernment policyzSoutheast Asia. 0aRight of propertyzSoutheast Asia. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Development / Sustainable Development.2bisacsh1 aAtkinson, Jane Monnig, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrenneis, Donald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ct